<Document>
<name>Trollstigen — Troll's Path</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Trollstigen — Troll's Path</h2><p><i>Møre og Romsdal, Norway · Rv63, Åndalsnes to Geiranger</i></p><p><b>11 hairpins climbing 858 m past Europe's tallest cliff, then ferry to a UNESCO fjord.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>70 km (44 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>3–4 hrs (plus ferry)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>Late May–September (closed Oct–late May for snow)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Closure dates uncertain, bus traffic on hairpins, weather, midges in summer, ferry schedule (book or wait)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>190</td></tr></table><hr><p>Trollstigen ('Troll's Path') is 11 numbered hairpins climbing 858 m in 9 km — opened by King Haakon VII in 1936 after eight years of construction. The Trollveggen (Troll Wall) on the approach is Europe's tallest vertical rock face at 1,100 m, and the highest BASE-jump site in Europe (illegally). After the pass you descend to the Romsdal valley and cross to Geiranger via a short car ferry from Linge to Eidsdal, then drive down the Eagle Road's 11 more hairpins to a fjord deep enough for cruise ships. Geirangerfjord is UNESCO World Heritage. Closes for snow late September to mid-May; check status.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Trollveggen viewpoint</b> — Pull-off on the approach to Trollstigen with face-on view of the Troll Wall — 1,100 m vertical rock face, Europe's tallest. Cloud-snagging, awe-inducing.</li><li><b>Trollstigen viewing platform</b> — 2012 designer cantilevered steel-and-concrete platform jutting over the abyss. Visitor center, restaurant. Stigfossen's 320 m drop is below.</li><li><b>Stigfossen waterfall</b> — 320 m falls dropping beside the road from the Stigsfossen lake above. Photographs from the lower hairpins are the iconic views of the road.</li><li><b>Valldal</b> — Strawberry capital of Norway — sheltered south-facing valley, intense flavor from the long midnight-sun days. Roadside stands all summer.</li><li><b>Eagle Road / Ørnesvingen</b> — 11 numbered hairpins descending into Geiranger. Top viewpoint is a 2010 platform with the fjord below and the Seven Sisters waterfall opposite.</li><li><b>Geirangerfjord</b> — UNESCO World Heritage. 15 km long, 1,500 m deep. Boat tours pass close to the Seven Sisters and the Suitor (waterfalls in courtship folklore). Cruise terminus; expect ships in summer.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
